  "text": "The baseflow after the snowmelt season of 2012 was consistently high compared with that in 2011 ( Figure 3 ). This is probably due to the high and long groundwater storage by relatively large snowmelt in March 2011 and the subsequent largest runoff event in early May. With respect to the snowmelt, the initial positive daily mean air temperature of 2011 and 2012 at the Taiki Aerospace Research Field and Taiki town was recorded on 13 March (2˚C) and 30 March (7.5˚C), respectively, when the snow depth at Taiki town was at 40 cm and 73 cm, respectively. Thereafter, covered snow in the catchment or around disappeared on 30 March 2011 and 19 April 2012. Calculation of the snowmelt amount by the degree-day approach [CITATION_1] indicated that the snowmelt amount in 2012 was two times as large as that in 2011.",
